  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a coinage probe?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **coinage probe** is a language-assessment prompt that asks someone to **create or “coin” a new word** based on a given situation, base word, or pattern.\n\nIt’s often used in linguistics, education, or speech-language pathology to test whether a person understands **word-formation rules**, such as adding suffixes or making new nouns/verbs.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A person who teaches is a teacher. A person who *zibs* is a ___?”\n\nExpected response: **zibber**\n\nThis shows whether the person can apply the pattern **verb + -er = person who does the action**.\n\nSo, in short: a **coinage probe** tests someone’s ability to generate a new word using language rules, rather than simply recall a word they already know.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "“Coinage probe” isn’t a widely standardized term, so its meaning depends on context.\n\nMost commonly, in a **language/linguistics or speech-language testing** context, a **coinage probe** is a prompt or test item used to see whether someone can **coin**, or create, a new word or form. For example, a child might be shown a made-up creature and asked what to call more than one of them, similar to the famous **“wug test.”** It probes productive word formation rather than memorized vocabulary.\n\nIn other fields, you might also see something like **“coinage-metal probe,”** meaning a probe involving coinage metals such as **copper, silver, or gold**.\n\nIf you saw the term in a specific article, class, or device manual, I can help pin down the exact meaning.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** and a **probing classifier** are both “probes,” but they probe very different things.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** is a **behavioral/task prompt**:  \n> “Can the subject generate a novel word using a morphological rule?”\n\nA **probing classifier** is an **analysis model trained on representations**:  \n> “Is some linguistic information encoded in a neural network’s hidden states?”\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA **coinage probe** asks a human, child, language learner, patient, or language model to **produce or judge a newly coined word**.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Someone who wugs is a ___?”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “wugger”\n\nThe goal is to test whether the subject can apply a word-formation rule, such as:\n\n> verb + `-er` → person who performs the action\n\nSo a coinage probe is usually about **productive linguistic competence**: can the subject use a rule on a novel item?\n\nIt is an **input-output test**. You give a prompt and observe the response.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Probing classifier\n\nA **probing classifier**, as in Alain & Bengio 2016 or Hewitt & Manning 2019, is different.\n\nThere, you take internal representations from a neural network — for example, BERT hidden states — and train a separate classifier or model to predict some linguistic property.\n\nExample:\n\n> Given a hidden vector for the word “dog,” can a classifier predict that it is a noun?\n\nOr in Hewitt & Manning’s structural probe:\n\n> Given contextual word representations, can a learned transformation recover syntactic tree distances?\n\nThe goal is not to see whether the original model can coin a word. The goal is to ask:\n\n> Is information about part of speech, syntax, dependency structure, tense, number, etc. present in the model’s internal representations?\n\nSo a probing classifier is a **diagnostic model** trained on top of representations.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Object being tested | Human, learner, patient, or LM behavior | Neural representation inside a model |\n| Method | Prompt the system and observe output | Train a classifier/regressor on hidden states |\n| Typical question | “Can it apply a word-formation rule?” | “Is this linguistic property encoded in the representation?” |\n| Output | A produced or judged novel word | Classifier accuracy, structural recovery score, etc. |\n| Requires training a probe model? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Example | “A person who zibs is a ___?” | “Can a linear classifier predict POS from layer 8 embeddings?” |\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA **coinage probe** tests **use** of linguistic knowledge.\n\nA **probing classifier** tests **accessibility of linguistic information in representations**.\n\nThose are related but not the same. A model might contain information in its hidden states that a probing classifier can extract, while the model itself may not use that information in generation. Conversely, a model might generate the right coined form without its internal representation making the relevant rule cleanly recoverable by a simple probe.\n\n---\n\n## In the context of language models\n\nIf you ask an LM:\n\n> “Someone who daxes is a ___?”\n\nand inspect its answer, that is closer to a **coinage probe** or **behavioral evaluation**.\n\nIf you take the LM’s hidden states for “daxes” and train a classifier to predict whether the word is a verb, singular, past tense, morphologically complex, etc., that is a **probing classifier** experiment.\n\nSo the key difference is:\n\n> **Coinage probe = prompt-based elicitation of novel word formation.**  \n> **Probing classifier = supervised diagnostic model trained to decode information from representations.**",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the system produce or judge a novel coined word using a word-formation pattern?\n\nA **behavioral probe / capability evaluation** asks more generally:\n\n> What can the system do, based on its observable input-output behavior?\n\nSo:\n\n> **Coinage probe ⊂ behavioral probe / capability evaluation**\n\nIt is a narrower, linguistically targeted behavioral test.\n\n---\n\n## Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe focuses specifically on **novel word formation**.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A person who gliffs is a ___?”\n\nPossible expected answer:\n\n> “gliffer”\n\nThis tests whether the subject can apply a productive morphological rule like:\n\n> verb + `-er` → agent noun\n\nThe key features are:\n\n- uses **novel or nonce words**\n- tests **productive morphology or lexical creativity**\n- usually requires **generation or judgment**\n- evaluates whether the subject can extend a pattern beyond memorized vocabulary\n\nSo if you ask an LM:\n\n> “Someone who daxes is called a ___?”\n\nand inspect whether it says:\n\n> “daxer”\n\nthat is a **coinage probe**.\n\n---\n\n## Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n\nA behavioral probe is much broader. It tests a model by giving it inputs and observing outputs, without necessarily inspecting hidden states.\n\nExamples:\n\n> “Translate this sentence into French.”  \n> “Solve this math problem.”  \n> “Is this sentence grammatical?”  \n> “Answer this question from the passage.”  \n> “Can you follow this instruction?”  \n> “What is the plural of wug?”\n\nThese are all behavioral tests because they evaluate the system externally, through behavior.\n\nA **capability evaluation** is often a larger-scale or more benchmark-like version of this. It may test abilities such as:\n\n- reasoning\n- translation\n- factual recall\n- tool use\n- syntactic judgment\n- morphology\n- instruction following\n- coding\n- safety behavior\n\nSo a capability evaluation may contain many behavioral probes, one of which could be a coinage probe.\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrow | Broad |\n| Target | Novel word formation, morphology, lexical productivity | Any observable capability |\n| Typical input | Nonce-word prompt | Any task prompt |\n| Typical output | Coined word or judgment of coined word | Answer, classification, action, explanation, etc. |\n| Example | “Someone who wugs is a ___?” | “Translate this,” “solve this,” “classify this,” etc. |\n| Relation | A subtype of behavioral probe | Superordinate category |\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A machine that blicks is a ___?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “blicker”\n\nThis tests whether the model can generalize a morphological pattern to a novel verb.\n\n### Behavioral probe, but not coinage\n\n> “What is the capital of Finland?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “Helsinki”\n\nThis is behavioral, because you judge the model by its answer, but it is not a coinage probe because it does not involve creating a novel word.\n\n### Capability evaluation\n\nA benchmark might include 500 tasks testing morphology, syntax, reasoning, and factual knowledge. A coinage probe could be one item or one subtest inside that broader evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## Important nuance\n\nA **behavioral probe** is about *how you evaluate*: by observing input-output behavior.\n\nA **coinage probe** is about *what you evaluate*: productive word formation.\n\nSo the difference is not methodological in the same way as with probing classifiers. Unlike probing classifiers, both coinage probes and behavioral probes operate at the level of observed behavior. The difference is mainly one of **specificity**:\n\n> **Coinage probe = a targeted behavioral probe for novel word formation.**  \n> **Behavioral probe / capability evaluation = any external test of what the system can do.**",
    "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** can both involve novel words, but they test different abilities.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the subject create or judge a new word by applying a word-formation rule?\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> Can the subject learn, remember, and use a new word and its meaning?\n\nSo:\n\n> **Coinage probe = productive word formation**  \n> **Lexical-acquisition test = learning a lexical item**\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe tests whether someone can generate a plausible new word from a linguistic pattern.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A person who blicks is a ___?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “blicker”\n\nThe subject does not need to have learned the word **blicker** before. The point is that they can apply a morphological rule:\n\n> verb + `-er` → person who performs the action\n\nOther examples:\n\n> “This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.”  \n> Expected: **wugs**\n\n> “Someone who mips is a ___.”  \n> Expected: **mipper**\n\nThe focus is on **rule productivity**, not on memorizing a new word.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lexical-acquisition test\n\nA lexical-acquisition test examines whether someone can learn a new word as a vocabulary item.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This object is called a dax.”  \n> Later: “Which one is the dax?”\n\nOr:\n\n> “A toma is a tool used for cutting rope.”  \n> Later: “What is a toma used for?”\n\nHere, the test is about whether the subject has acquired a new **form–meaning mapping**:\n\n> **dax** ↔ a particular object  \n> **toma** ↔ a particular tool or concept\n\nThe focus is on:\n\n- learning a new word\n- remembering it\n- mapping it to a referent or meaning\n- generalizing it appropriately\n- using it later in comprehension or production\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the subject form a new word by rule? | Can the subject learn a new word and its meaning? |\n| Target ability | Morphological productivity / word formation | Vocabulary learning / form–meaning mapping |\n| Novel word role | Often a stem used to elicit a derived form | The item to be learned |\n| Requires prior teaching? | Usually no, beyond the pattern | Usually yes, through exposure or instruction |\n| Example | “One who zibs is a ___?” → **zibber** | “This is a zib. Which object is the zib?” |\n| Correctness depends on | Applying a linguistic pattern | Remembering or inferring the lexical meaning |\n\n---\n\n## Key contrast\n\nIn a **coinage probe**, the novel word is usually a prompt for generating another form.\n\n> “Someone who gliffs is a ___?”  \n> “gliffer”\n\nThe subject is not being asked to learn that **gliffer** is a conventional word. They are being asked to produce a plausible coined form.\n\nIn a **lexical-acquisition test**, the novel word itself is the thing to be learned.\n\n> “This creature is called a gliff.”  \n> Later: “Point to the gliff.”\n\nThe subject must remember that **gliff** names that creature.\n\n---\n\n## Important overlap\n\nThere can be overlap. A lexical-acquisition experiment might teach a novel word and then test whether the learner can inflect or derive it.\n\nExample:\n\n> Training: “This action is called to blick.”  \n> Test: “Yesterday she ___.”  \n> Expected: **blicked**\n\nThis includes both:\n\n1. **lexical acquisition**: learning that **blick** names an action  \n2. **coinage/morphological productivity**: forming **blicked**\n\nSo the distinction is not that one uses novel words and the other does not. Both can. The difference is what is being measured.\n\n---\n\n## In one sentence\n\nA **coinage probe** tests whether someone can **create a new word using linguistic rules**, while a **lexical-acquisition test** tests whether someone can **learn and retain a new word as part of their vocabulary**."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"coinage probe\": A Coinage Probe is a methodology that introduces a coined term to a model in a fresh chat, measures its cold-state confabulation against a named set of near-neighbors, then introduces a single-sentence definition and re-measures distinguishability against the same neighbors — using the gap between the two measurements (Lexical Reachability) as evidence about the substrate on which the model's cognition runs. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition of “coinage probe” you provided.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed, how the probe is applied, and what kind of evidence it produces*.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier / structural probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Canonical examples | Your definition: introduce a new coined term, test cold confabulation, give one-sentence definition, retest distinguishability | Alain & Bengio 2016 linear classifiers on hidden layers; Hewitt & Manning 2019 structural probes for syntax |\n| Access required | Can be black-box: only need model I/O | Usually requires access to internal activations/representations |\n| Intervention | Introduces a novel lexical item into the conversation | Usually freezes a trained model and trains an auxiliary classifier/regressor on its representations |\n| Measurement target | Behavioral uptake of a new coined term relative to near-neighbors | Encoded information in hidden states, e.g. POS, syntax, parse distance |\n| Training involved | No auxiliary model training is necessary; the “probe” is the prompt protocol and measurement | Trains a diagnostic classifier or learned projection on representations |\n| Time scale | Measures immediate in-context lexical assimilation: before vs after definition | Measures information already present in representations after pretraining/fine-tuning |\n| Output evidence | A behavioral gap: cold-state confabulation vs post-definition distinguishability, i.e. “Lexical Reachability” | Classifier accuracy, selectivity, structural reconstruction quality, or related metrics |\n| Main question | “Can the model acquire and distinguish this new coined concept from nearby concepts in-context?” | “Is property X linearly or simply decodable from layer Y’s representation?” |\n\nSo, a **probing classifier** asks something like:\n\n> Given a model’s hidden representation at some layer, can a trained classifier recover syntactic or semantic property X?\n\nA **coinage probe** asks something more like:\n\n> Given a fresh coined term, how does the model behave before it knows the definition, and how sharply does its behavior change after receiving a minimal definition?\n\nThe key distinction is that probing classifiers are usually **representation-level diagnostic tools**, whereas coinage probes are **behavioral/in-context lexical acquisition tests**.\n\nThere is also a methodological difference. In Alain & Bengio-style probing, the probe itself can become a source of ambiguity: if a classifier succeeds, it may be because the information was genuinely represented, or because the probe learned a complex mapping. Hewitt & Manning addressed this by constraining the probe, for example using a structural geometry. A coinage probe avoids training an external probe, but introduces different confounds: prompt sensitivity, prior associations with morphemes, analogy to nearby words, instruction-following artifacts, and the choice of near-neighbor set.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Probing classifiers test what is decodable from internal states; coinage probes test how a model behaviorally incorporates and distinguishes a newly defined symbol in context.**",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specialized behavioral probe**, but it differs from ordinary behavioral probes or capability evaluations in its structure and target.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic form | Introduce a newly coined term, measure behavior before and after giving a definition | Ask the model to perform tasks and measure success |\n| Key intervention | A single new lexical item plus a minimal definition | Usually no controlled lexical intervention |\n| Baseline | Explicit cold-state measurement before the model is told the meaning | Often no pre-intervention baseline |\n| Comparison set | Uses named near-neighbors to test distinguishability | May use benchmarks, task examples, rubrics, or adversarial items |\n| Main metric | Gap between cold confabulation and post-definition distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability** | Accuracy, pass rate, calibration, robustness, human preference, task score, etc. |\n| What it tests | In-context uptake and separation of a new concept from adjacent concepts | General ability to perform some behavior or task |\n| Epistemic aim | Evidence about how readily a new symbol/concept becomes usable in the model’s cognition | Evidence about whether the model can do X under specified conditions |\n\nSo the difference is not that coinage probes are non-behavioral. They are behavioral. The difference is that they have a **very specific experimental shape**:\n\n1. Start a fresh chat.\n2. Present or query a coined term without defining it.\n3. Measure the model’s cold-state confabulation or nearest-neighbor collapse.\n4. Introduce a minimal definition.\n5. Re-test against the same near-neighbor set.\n6. Use the before/after gap as the signal.\n\nA normal behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> Can the model solve syllogisms, identify sarcasm, follow safety instructions, or answer medical questions?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more specific:\n\n> When given a brand-new label for a newly defined concept, can the model immediately bind that label to the intended meaning and distinguish it from nearby concepts it already knows?\n\nA capability evaluation usually measures **competence on an existing task distribution**. For example, “Can the model answer MMLU chemistry questions?” or “Can it write working Python?” A coinage probe instead measures **lexical-conceptual assimilation under controlled novelty**. It is less about whether the model already knows a domain and more about how it handles a newly introduced conceptual handle.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A behavioral probe tests behavior. A capability evaluation scores performance. A coinage probe is a controlled behavioral intervention that tests how a model moves from ignorance/confabulation about a novel term to in-context distinguishability after a minimal definition.\n\nSo a coinage probe can be considered a **particular kind of behavioral probe**, but it is narrower, pre/post structured, explicitly lexical, and centered on the measurement called **Lexical Reachability**.",
    "A **coinage probe** overlaps with a **lexical-acquisition test**, but it is narrower and has a different epistemic purpose.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic question | How does a model behave around a newly coined term before and after a minimal definition? | Can a learner acquire the meaning/use of a new word? |\n| Subject | Usually an LLM/model in a fresh chat | Humans, children, second-language learners, animals, or models |\n| Novel term | Essential: the term is coined or newly introduced | Often uses novel words, but may also test real vocabulary learning |\n| Baseline | Explicit cold-state test before definition | May or may not include a pretest |\n| Intervention | Typically a single-sentence definition | Can involve repeated exposure, examples, contrastive learning, ostension, feedback, stories, images, etc. |\n| Comparison target | A named set of near-neighbors | May test recall, comprehension, production, generalization, retention, mapping to referents, etc. |\n| Main measurement | Difference between cold confabulation and post-definition distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability** | Degree of word learning or vocabulary acquisition |\n| Time scale | Immediate in-context uptake | Immediate, delayed, longitudinal, developmental, or training-based |\n| Epistemic aim | Evidence about the model’s internal cognitive substrate or representational dynamics | Evidence about whether and how a word meaning was learned |\n\nSo a lexical-acquisition test might ask:\n\n> After hearing the word “blicket” paired with an object several times, can a child identify another blicket later?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more specific:\n\n> Before the model is told what “coinage probe” means, does it collapse the term into nearby known concepts? After receiving a one-sentence definition, can it distinguish the coined term from those same near-neighbors?\n\nThe key difference is that **lexical-acquisition tests primarily evaluate word learning**, while a **coinage probe uses controlled word learning as an instrument**. The coined word is not the final object of interest; it is a probe for how the model binds a new symbol, separates it from semantically adjacent concepts, and changes behavior after minimal in-context definition.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A coinage probe is a specialized, pre/post, near-neighbor-controlled lexical-acquisition-style test whose distinctive metric is Lexical Reachability and whose purpose is to infer something about model cognition, not merely vocabulary learning."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **coinage probe** can mean different things depending on the context, but most often it refers to a **test or assessment item used to see whether someone can create or understand newly coined words**.\n\nFor example, in **language/linguistics or speech-language assessment**, a coinage probe might ask a person to form a new word from a base word or to interpret a made-up word, such as:\n\n- “A person who paints is a painter. What do you call a person who zibs?” → “zibber”\n- “If something is ‘blickish,’ what might that mean?”\n\nIt “probes” the ability to use word-formation rules, such as prefixes, suffixes, and derivational morphology.\n\nIf you mean it in another field—like **metal detecting, numismatics, education, or psychology**—tell me the context and I can give the more specific definition.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed* and *how*.\n\n### Short version\n\n- A **coinage probe** is usually a **behavioral/input probe**: you introduce a newly coined or nonce word and test whether a person/model can interpret, inflect, derive, or use it appropriately.\n- A **probing classifier** is a **diagnostic model trained on internal representations**: you freeze a neural model’s representations and train a classifier or regressor to predict some linguistic property from them.\n\nSo a coinage probe asks:\n\n> “Can the system generalize to a novel word?”\n\nA probing classifier asks:\n\n> “Is information about some property recoverable from the model’s hidden states?”\n\n---\n\n## Example: coinage probe\n\nSuppose you give a language model:\n\n> A “blicket” is a small tool used to open jars.  \n> Yesterday, Maria used the blicket. What did she use?\n\nYou then test whether the model understands that **blicket** refers to the newly introduced tool.\n\nOr in morphology:\n\n> Someone who “daxes” is a ___?\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> daxer\n\nThis probes **productive word formation**, **nonce-word generalization**, or **lexical learning**.\n\nNo separate classifier needs to be trained. The model is tested directly through its behavior.\n\n---\n\n## Example: probing classifier\n\nFollowing work such as **Alain & Bengio 2016** or **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, you might take hidden states from a language model and train a lightweight supervised model on top.\n\nFor example:\n\n1. Run sentences through BERT or another model.\n2. Extract hidden vectors.\n3. Train a classifier to predict part of speech:\n\n> hidden state of “dog” → NOUN  \n> hidden state of “runs” → VERB\n\nOr, in **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, train a structural probe to see whether syntactic tree distances can be recovered from word representations.\n\nThe underlying model is usually frozen. The probe is trained to ask:\n\n> “Does this representation encode syntax, morphology, tense, number, dependency structure, etc.?”\n\n---\n\n## Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main object of study | Model/person’s behavior on novel words | Information encoded in hidden representations |\n| Requires training an auxiliary model? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Uses internal activations? | Not necessarily | Yes |\n| Typical data | Nonce words, neologisms, invented forms | Labeled linguistic datasets |\n| Typical question | “Can the model generalize productively?” | “Can this property be decoded from representations?” |\n| Example | “What is a daxer?” | Train classifier to predict POS from embeddings |\n| Evaluation | Accuracy/quality of responses to novel forms | Probe accuracy, selectivity, structural fit, etc. |\n\n---\n\n## Important conceptual distinction\n\nA **coinage probe** is closer to a **behavioral generalization test**. It manipulates the input by introducing unfamiliar lexical material and observes the system’s output.\n\nA **probing classifier** is closer to a **representational diagnostic**. It does not primarily test whether the model behaves correctly in a natural setting; it tests whether some information is accessible from the model’s learned vectors.\n\nFor example, a model might handle a coined word correctly in context even if a simple linear probe cannot decode a clean lexical category from its hidden state. Conversely, a probe might decode part-of-speech information from hidden states even if the model behaves poorly on nonce-word generalization.\n\n---\n\n## How they can be combined\n\nYou could combine the two methods. For instance:\n\n1. Introduce nonce words like **dax**, **blicket**, or **wug**.\n2. Run sentences containing those words through a language model.\n3. Extract hidden representations of the nonce words.\n4. Train or evaluate a probe to see whether the model represents their syntactic category, number, semantic role, or morphological features.\n\nThen the coined words provide the **stimuli**, while the probing classifier provides the **analysis method**.\n\nBut by itself, a coinage probe is not the same thing as a probing classifier. It is a test of **novel-word generalization**, whereas probing classifiers are tools for analyzing **what information is encoded in neural representations**.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe / capability evaluation**, not a fundamentally separate category.\n\nThe difference is mainly one of **scope and stimulus design**.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Behavioral probe / capability evaluation**: broad category. You test a model by giving it inputs and observing outputs.\n- **Coinage probe**: narrower subtype. You specifically use **newly coined / nonce words** to test whether the model can generalize beyond memorized vocabulary.\n\nSo:\n\n> A coinage probe is a behavioral probe whose key manipulation is the introduction of novel words or novel word forms.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a general behavioral probe\n\nYou might ask:\n\n> The trophy did not fit in the suitcase because it was too large.  \n> What was too large?\n\nExpected:\n\n> The trophy.\n\nThis is a behavioral probe of **coreference resolution** or commonsense reasoning.\n\nNo invented words are involved.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a coinage probe\n\nYou might ask:\n\n> A “dax” is a tool used to remove seeds from fruit.  \n> Sarah used the dax on an apple. What did Sarah use?\n\nExpected:\n\n> The dax, a seed-removing tool.\n\nOr:\n\n> This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> wugs.\n\nThis is also behavioral, but it specifically probes whether the system can handle a **novel lexical item**.\n\n---\n\n## Key distinction\n\n| Dimension | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation | Coinage probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Broad | Narrow |\n| Main method | Give inputs, inspect outputs | Give inputs containing coined/nonce words |\n| What it tests | Any capability: reasoning, syntax, factuality, planning, etc. | Novel-word learning, morphology, compositionality, abstraction |\n| Requires internal model access? | No | No |\n| Requires invented words? | Not necessarily | Yes, typically |\n| Example | “Can the model solve syllogisms?” | “Can the model infer what a ‘blicket’ is?” |\n\n---\n\n## Conceptual relationship\n\nA **coinage probe** is usually a **behavioral capability evaluation**, but with a special purpose: reducing reliance on memorized lexical knowledge.\n\nFor example, if you test:\n\n> A baker bakes bread. What does a teacher teach?\n\nThe model may answer from memorized language statistics.\n\nBut if you test:\n\n> A daxer daxes things. What does a glipper do?\n\nyou are testing whether the model can infer patterns from structure rather than simply recall familiar word associations.\n\nThat makes coinage probes useful for evaluating:\n\n- **productive morphology**\n- **nonce-word generalization**\n- **in-context lexical learning**\n- **syntactic category inference**\n- **semantic role assignment**\n- **compositional reasoning with unfamiliar terms**\n- **abstraction away from memorized vocabulary**\n\n---\n\n## Important nuance\n\nNot every behavioral probe is a coinage probe, but most coinage probes are behavioral probes.\n\nThe relationship is roughly:\n\n> capability evaluation  \n> → behavioral probe  \n> → coinage/nonce-word probe\n\nA coinage probe is therefore not an alternative to behavioral evaluation; it is a particular design strategy within behavioral evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## How it differs from ordinary capability evaluation\n\nA standard capability evaluation might ask:\n\n> Can the model translate French?  \n> Can it solve math problems?  \n> Can it answer biology questions?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more controlled:\n\n> If I remove familiar lexical items and replace them with invented ones, does the model still display the relevant ability?\n\nFor example, instead of testing arithmetic with familiar nouns:\n\n> Alice has 3 apples and gets 2 more apples. How many apples?\n\nyou might use coined terms:\n\n> Alice has 3 daxes and gets 2 more daxes. How many daxes?\n\nThis checks whether the model’s arithmetic behavior survives when familiar semantic cues are stripped away.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nA **coinage probe** is a **specific behavioral probe** using invented words to test generalization. A **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is the broader category of input-output tests of what a model can do. The distinctive value of coinage probes is that they help separate **true abstraction/generalization** from **memorized associations with familiar words**.",
    "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** overlap, but they are not identical.\n\n## Short version\n\n- A **coinage probe** uses **coined / nonce words** as stimuli to test whether a system can generalize beyond familiar vocabulary.\n- A **lexical-acquisition test** specifically tests whether a learner or model can **learn and retain a new lexical item**, usually including its meaning, usage, syntactic category, or associations.\n\nSo:\n\n> A lexical-acquisition test asks: “Did the system learn this new word?”  \n> A coinage probe asks more broadly: “How does the system handle an invented word?”\n\nA lexical-acquisition test can use coinages, but not every coinage probe is a lexical-acquisition test.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a lexical-acquisition test\n\nYou introduce a new word:\n\n> A **blicket** is a small tool used for opening jars.\n\nThen later ask:\n\n> What is a blicket?  \n> Which object is the blicket?  \n> Can a blicket be used to open a jar?  \n> Maria lost her blicket. What did she lose?\n\nThis tests whether the model or person acquired the lexical entry:\n\n> **blicket** → small jar-opening tool\n\nThe focus is on **learning a new word meaning** and possibly retaining or applying it.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a coinage probe that is not mainly lexical acquisition\n\nYou ask:\n\n> This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> wugs.\n\nHere the point is not primarily whether the person learned a rich meaning for **wug**. The point is whether they apply the English plural rule to a novel noun.\n\nThat is a **coinage probe** of **productive morphology**, not necessarily a lexical-acquisition test.\n\nAnother example:\n\n> Someone who daxes is a ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> daxer.\n\nAgain, the focus is word-formation generalization, not learning the meaning of **dax**.\n\n---\n\n## Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Broader | Narrower in purpose |\n| Main manipulation | Use invented / nonce words | Teach or expose a learner to a new word |\n| Main question | “Can the system handle novel lexical material?” | “Has the system learned this word?” |\n| Typical target | Morphology, syntax, compositionality, abstraction, in-context learning | Word meaning, reference, usage, retention |\n| Requires assigning a meaning? | Not always | Usually yes |\n| Requires testing retention? | Not necessarily | Often yes |\n| Example | “Two wugs” | “What is a blicket?” after exposure |\n| Relation | May include lexical learning | May use coined words as materials |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test can be implemented as a coinage probe** if the word being learned is invented.\n\nFor example:\n\n> A **toma** is a red triangular toy.  \n> Point to the toma.\n\nThis is both:\n\n1. a **coinage probe**, because **toma** is novel, and  \n2. a **lexical-acquisition test**, because the task is to learn and use the new word.\n\nBut a coinage probe can test things other than lexical acquisition, such as:\n\n- pluralization: **wug → wugs**\n- derivation: **dax → daxer**\n- syntactic category inference: “She blicked the ball” implies **blick** is a verb\n- compositionality: “red blicket” versus “small blicket”\n- analogy: “A painter paints; a glommer gloms”\n- robustness to unfamiliar vocabulary\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA lexical-acquisition test usually cares about the formation of a **new lexical entry**:\n\n> form + meaning + syntactic behavior + possible usage constraints\n\nA coinage probe may care only about whether the model can apply an existing rule to an unfamiliar form.\n\nFor instance:\n\n> There are two daxes.\n\nA model does not need to know what a **dax** is to pluralize it correctly. It only needs to infer that **dax** behaves like a count noun.\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n> **Lexical-acquisition test:** learning a word.  \n> **Coinage probe:** using a made-up word to test some capability, which may or may not involve learning the word."
