      {
        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **probing classifier** are both “probes,” but they probe very different things.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** is a **behavioral/task prompt**:  \n> “Can the subject generate a novel word using a morphological rule?”\n\nA **probing classifier** is an **analysis model trained on representations**:  \n> “Is some linguistic information encoded in a neural network’s hidden states?”\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA **coinage probe** asks a human, child, language learner, patient, or language model to **produce or judge a newly coined word**.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Someone who wugs is a ___?”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “wugger”\n\nThe goal is to test whether the subject can apply a word-formation rule, such as:\n\n> verb + `-er` → person who performs the action\n\nSo a coinage probe is usually about **productive linguistic competence**: can the subject use a rule on a novel item?\n\nIt is an **input-output test**. You give a prompt and observe the response.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Probing classifier\n\nA **probing classifier**, as in Alain & Bengio 2016 or Hewitt & Manning 2019, is different.\n\nThere, you take internal representations from a neural network — for example, BERT hidden states — and train a separate classifier or model to predict some linguistic property.\n\nExample:\n\n> Given a hidden vector for the word “dog,” can a classifier predict that it is a noun?\n\nOr in Hewitt & Manning’s structural probe:\n\n> Given contextual word representations, can a learned transformation recover syntactic tree distances?\n\nThe goal is not to see whether the original model can coin a word. The goal is to ask:\n\n> Is information about part of speech, syntax, dependency structure, tense, number, etc. present in the model’s internal representations?\n\nSo a probing classifier is a **diagnostic model** trained on top of representations.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Object being tested | Human, learner, patient, or LM behavior | Neural representation inside a model |\n| Method | Prompt the system and observe output | Train a classifier/regressor on hidden states |\n| Typical question | “Can it apply a word-formation rule?” | “Is this linguistic property encoded in the representation?” |\n| Output | A produced or judged novel word | Classifier accuracy, structural recovery score, etc. |\n| Requires training a probe model? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Example | “A person who zibs is a ___?” | “Can a linear classifier predict POS from layer 8 embeddings?” |\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA **coinage probe** tests **use** of linguistic knowledge.\n\nA **probing classifier** tests **accessibility of linguistic information in representations**.\n\nThose are related but not the same. A model might contain information in its hidden states that a probing classifier can extract, while the model itself may not use that information in generation. Conversely, a model might generate the right coined form without its internal representation making the relevant rule cleanly recoverable by a simple probe.\n\n---\n\n## In the context of language models\n\nIf you ask an LM:\n\n> “Someone who daxes is a ___?”\n\nand inspect its answer, that is closer to a **coinage probe** or **behavioral evaluation**.\n\nIf you take the LM’s hidden states for “daxes” and train a classifier to predict whether the word is a verb, singular, past tense, morphologically complex, etc., that is a **probing classifier** experiment.\n\nSo the key difference is:\n\n> **Coinage probe = prompt-based elicitation of novel word formation.**  \n> **Probing classifier = supervised diagnostic model trained to decode information from representations.**",
