        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the system produce or judge a novel coined word using a word-formation pattern?\n\nA **behavioral probe / capability evaluation** asks more generally:\n\n> What can the system do, based on its observable input-output behavior?\n\nSo:\n\n> **Coinage probe ⊂ behavioral probe / capability evaluation**\n\nIt is a narrower, linguistically targeted behavioral test.\n\n---\n\n## Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe focuses specifically on **novel word formation**.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A person who gliffs is a ___?”\n\nPossible expected answer:\n\n> “gliffer”\n\nThis tests whether the subject can apply a productive morphological rule like:\n\n> verb + `-er` → agent noun\n\nThe key features are:\n\n- uses **novel or nonce words**\n- tests **productive morphology or lexical creativity**\n- usually requires **generation or judgment**\n- evaluates whether the subject can extend a pattern beyond memorized vocabulary\n\nSo if you ask an LM:\n\n> “Someone who daxes is called a ___?”\n\nand inspect whether it says:\n\n> “daxer”\n\nthat is a **coinage probe**.\n\n---\n\n## Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n\nA behavioral probe is much broader. It tests a model by giving it inputs and observing outputs, without necessarily inspecting hidden states.\n\nExamples:\n\n> “Translate this sentence into French.”  \n> “Solve this math problem.”  \n> “Is this sentence grammatical?”  \n> “Answer this question from the passage.”  \n> “Can you follow this instruction?”  \n> “What is the plural of wug?”\n\nThese are all behavioral tests because they evaluate the system externally, through behavior.\n\nA **capability evaluation** is often a larger-scale or more benchmark-like version of this. It may test abilities such as:\n\n- reasoning\n- translation\n- factual recall\n- tool use\n- syntactic judgment\n- morphology\n- instruction following\n- coding\n- safety behavior\n\nSo a capability evaluation may contain many behavioral probes, one of which could be a coinage probe.\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrow | Broad |\n| Target | Novel word formation, morphology, lexical productivity | Any observable capability |\n| Typical input | Nonce-word prompt | Any task prompt |\n| Typical output | Coined word or judgment of coined word | Answer, classification, action, explanation, etc. |\n| Example | “Someone who wugs is a ___?” | “Translate this,” “solve this,” “classify this,” etc. |\n| Relation | A subtype of behavioral probe | Superordinate category |\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A machine that blicks is a ___?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “blicker”\n\nThis tests whether the model can generalize a morphological pattern to a novel verb.\n\n### Behavioral probe, but not coinage\n\n> “What is the capital of Finland?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “Helsinki”\n\nThis is behavioral, because you judge the model by its answer, but it is not a coinage probe because it does not involve creating a novel word.\n\n### Capability evaluation\n\nA benchmark might include 500 tasks testing morphology, syntax, reasoning, and factual knowledge. A coinage probe could be one item or one subtest inside that broader evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## Important nuance\n\nA **behavioral probe** is about *how you evaluate*: by observing input-output behavior.\n\nA **coinage probe** is about *what you evaluate*: productive word formation.\n\nSo the difference is not methodological in the same way as with probing classifiers. Unlike probing classifiers, both coinage probes and behavioral probes operate at the level of observed behavior. The difference is mainly one of **specificity**:\n\n> **Coinage probe = a targeted behavioral probe for novel word formation.**  \n> **Behavioral probe / capability evaluation = any external test of what the system can do.**",
