        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** can both involve novel words, but they test different abilities.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the subject create or judge a new word by applying a word-formation rule?\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> Can the subject learn, remember, and use a new word and its meaning?\n\nSo:\n\n> **Coinage probe = productive word formation**  \n> **Lexical-acquisition test = learning a lexical item**\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe tests whether someone can generate a plausible new word from a linguistic pattern.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A person who blicks is a ___?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “blicker”\n\nThe subject does not need to have learned the word **blicker** before. The point is that they can apply a morphological rule:\n\n> verb + `-er` → person who performs the action\n\nOther examples:\n\n> “This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.”  \n> Expected: **wugs**\n\n> “Someone who mips is a ___.”  \n> Expected: **mipper**\n\nThe focus is on **rule productivity**, not on memorizing a new word.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lexical-acquisition test\n\nA lexical-acquisition test examines whether someone can learn a new word as a vocabulary item.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This object is called a dax.”  \n> Later: “Which one is the dax?”\n\nOr:\n\n> “A toma is a tool used for cutting rope.”  \n> Later: “What is a toma used for?”\n\nHere, the test is about whether the subject has acquired a new **form–meaning mapping**:\n\n> **dax** ↔ a particular object  \n> **toma** ↔ a particular tool or concept\n\nThe focus is on:\n\n- learning a new word\n- remembering it\n- mapping it to a referent or meaning\n- generalizing it appropriately\n- using it later in comprehension or production\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the subject form a new word by rule? | Can the subject learn a new word and its meaning? |\n| Target ability | Morphological productivity / word formation | Vocabulary learning / form–meaning mapping |\n| Novel word role | Often a stem used to elicit a derived form | The item to be learned |\n| Requires prior teaching? | Usually no, beyond the pattern | Usually yes, through exposure or instruction |\n| Example | “One who zibs is a ___?” → **zibber** | “This is a zib. Which object is the zib?” |\n| Correctness depends on | Applying a linguistic pattern | Remembering or inferring the lexical meaning |\n\n---\n\n## Key contrast\n\nIn a **coinage probe**, the novel word is usually a prompt for generating another form.\n\n> “Someone who gliffs is a ___?”  \n> “gliffer”\n\nThe subject is not being asked to learn that **gliffer** is a conventional word. They are being asked to produce a plausible coined form.\n\nIn a **lexical-acquisition test**, the novel word itself is the thing to be learned.\n\n> “This creature is called a gliff.”  \n> Later: “Point to the gliff.”\n\nThe subject must remember that **gliff** names that creature.\n\n---\n\n## Important overlap\n\nThere can be overlap. A lexical-acquisition experiment might teach a novel word and then test whether the learner can inflect or derive it.\n\nExample:\n\n> Training: “This action is called to blick.”  \n> Test: “Yesterday she ___.”  \n> Expected: **blicked**\n\nThis includes both:\n\n1. **lexical acquisition**: learning that **blick** names an action  \n2. **coinage/morphological productivity**: forming **blicked**\n\nSo the distinction is not that one uses novel words and the other does not. Both can. The difference is what is being measured.\n\n---\n\n## In one sentence\n\nA **coinage probe** tests whether someone can **create a new word using linguistic rules**, while a **lexical-acquisition test** tests whether someone can **learn and retain a new word as part of their vocabulary**.",
