        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed, how the probe is applied, and what kind of evidence it produces*.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier / structural probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Canonical examples | Your definition: introduce a new coined term, test cold confabulation, give one-sentence definition, retest distinguishability | Alain & Bengio 2016 linear classifiers on hidden layers; Hewitt & Manning 2019 structural probes for syntax |\n| Access required | Can be black-box: only need model I/O | Usually requires access to internal activations/representations |\n| Intervention | Introduces a novel lexical item into the conversation | Usually freezes a trained model and trains an auxiliary classifier/regressor on its representations |\n| Measurement target | Behavioral uptake of a new coined term relative to near-neighbors | Encoded information in hidden states, e.g. POS, syntax, parse distance |\n| Training involved | No auxiliary model training is necessary; the “probe” is the prompt protocol and measurement | Trains a diagnostic classifier or learned projection on representations |\n| Time scale | Measures immediate in-context lexical assimilation: before vs after definition | Measures information already present in representations after pretraining/fine-tuning |\n| Output evidence | A behavioral gap: cold-state confabulation vs post-definition distinguishability, i.e. “Lexical Reachability” | Classifier accuracy, selectivity, structural reconstruction quality, or related metrics |\n| Main question | “Can the model acquire and distinguish this new coined concept from nearby concepts in-context?” | “Is property X linearly or simply decodable from layer Y’s representation?” |\n\nSo, a **probing classifier** asks something like:\n\n> Given a model’s hidden representation at some layer, can a trained classifier recover syntactic or semantic property X?\n\nA **coinage probe** asks something more like:\n\n> Given a fresh coined term, how does the model behave before it knows the definition, and how sharply does its behavior change after receiving a minimal definition?\n\nThe key distinction is that probing classifiers are usually **representation-level diagnostic tools**, whereas coinage probes are **behavioral/in-context lexical acquisition tests**.\n\nThere is also a methodological difference. In Alain & Bengio-style probing, the probe itself can become a source of ambiguity: if a classifier succeeds, it may be because the information was genuinely represented, or because the probe learned a complex mapping. Hewitt & Manning addressed this by constraining the probe, for example using a structural geometry. A coinage probe avoids training an external probe, but introduces different confounds: prompt sensitivity, prior associations with morphemes, analogy to nearby words, instruction-following artifacts, and the choice of near-neighbor set.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Probing classifiers test what is decodable from internal states; coinage probes test how a model behaviorally incorporates and distinguishes a newly defined symbol in context.**",
