      {
        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specialized behavioral probe**, but it differs from ordinary behavioral probes or capability evaluations in its structure and target.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic form | Introduce a newly coined term, measure behavior before and after giving a definition | Ask the model to perform tasks and measure success |\n| Key intervention | A single new lexical item plus a minimal definition | Usually no controlled lexical intervention |\n| Baseline | Explicit cold-state measurement before the model is told the meaning | Often no pre-intervention baseline |\n| Comparison set | Uses named near-neighbors to test distinguishability | May use benchmarks, task examples, rubrics, or adversarial items |\n| Main metric | Gap between cold confabulation and post-definition distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability** | Accuracy, pass rate, calibration, robustness, human preference, task score, etc. |\n| What it tests | In-context uptake and separation of a new concept from adjacent concepts | General ability to perform some behavior or task |\n| Epistemic aim | Evidence about how readily a new symbol/concept becomes usable in the model’s cognition | Evidence about whether the model can do X under specified conditions |\n\nSo the difference is not that coinage probes are non-behavioral. They are behavioral. The difference is that they have a **very specific experimental shape**:\n\n1. Start a fresh chat.\n2. Present or query a coined term without defining it.\n3. Measure the model’s cold-state confabulation or nearest-neighbor collapse.\n4. Introduce a minimal definition.\n5. Re-test against the same near-neighbor set.\n6. Use the before/after gap as the signal.\n\nA normal behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> Can the model solve syllogisms, identify sarcasm, follow safety instructions, or answer medical questions?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more specific:\n\n> When given a brand-new label for a newly defined concept, can the model immediately bind that label to the intended meaning and distinguish it from nearby concepts it already knows?\n\nA capability evaluation usually measures **competence on an existing task distribution**. For example, “Can the model answer MMLU chemistry questions?” or “Can it write working Python?” A coinage probe instead measures **lexical-conceptual assimilation under controlled novelty**. It is less about whether the model already knows a domain and more about how it handles a newly introduced conceptual handle.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A behavioral probe tests behavior. A capability evaluation scores performance. A coinage probe is a controlled behavioral intervention that tests how a model moves from ignorance/confabulation about a novel term to in-context distinguishability after a minimal definition.\n\nSo a coinage probe can be considered a **particular kind of behavioral probe**, but it is narrower, pre/post structured, explicitly lexical, and centered on the measurement called **Lexical Reachability**.",
