        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** overlaps with a **lexical-acquisition test**, but it is narrower and has a different epistemic purpose.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic question | How does a model behave around a newly coined term before and after a minimal definition? | Can a learner acquire the meaning/use of a new word? |\n| Subject | Usually an LLM/model in a fresh chat | Humans, children, second-language learners, animals, or models |\n| Novel term | Essential: the term is coined or newly introduced | Often uses novel words, but may also test real vocabulary learning |\n| Baseline | Explicit cold-state test before definition | May or may not include a pretest |\n| Intervention | Typically a single-sentence definition | Can involve repeated exposure, examples, contrastive learning, ostension, feedback, stories, images, etc. |\n| Comparison target | A named set of near-neighbors | May test recall, comprehension, production, generalization, retention, mapping to referents, etc. |\n| Main measurement | Difference between cold confabulation and post-definition distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability** | Degree of word learning or vocabulary acquisition |\n| Time scale | Immediate in-context uptake | Immediate, delayed, longitudinal, developmental, or training-based |\n| Epistemic aim | Evidence about the model’s internal cognitive substrate or representational dynamics | Evidence about whether and how a word meaning was learned |\n\nSo a lexical-acquisition test might ask:\n\n> After hearing the word “blicket” paired with an object several times, can a child identify another blicket later?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more specific:\n\n> Before the model is told what “coinage probe” means, does it collapse the term into nearby known concepts? After receiving a one-sentence definition, can it distinguish the coined term from those same near-neighbors?\n\nThe key difference is that **lexical-acquisition tests primarily evaluate word learning**, while a **coinage probe uses controlled word learning as an instrument**. The coined word is not the final object of interest; it is a probe for how the model binds a new symbol, separates it from semantically adjacent concepts, and changes behavior after minimal in-context definition.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A coinage probe is a specialized, pre/post, near-neighbor-controlled lexical-acquisition-style test whose distinctive metric is Lexical Reachability and whose purpose is to infer something about model cognition, not merely vocabulary learning.",
