        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe / capability evaluation**, not a fundamentally separate category.\n\nThe difference is mainly one of **scope and stimulus design**.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Behavioral probe / capability evaluation**: broad category. You test a model by giving it inputs and observing outputs.\n- **Coinage probe**: narrower subtype. You specifically use **newly coined / nonce words** to test whether the model can generalize beyond memorized vocabulary.\n\nSo:\n\n> A coinage probe is a behavioral probe whose key manipulation is the introduction of novel words or novel word forms.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a general behavioral probe\n\nYou might ask:\n\n> The trophy did not fit in the suitcase because it was too large.  \n> What was too large?\n\nExpected:\n\n> The trophy.\n\nThis is a behavioral probe of **coreference resolution** or commonsense reasoning.\n\nNo invented words are involved.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a coinage probe\n\nYou might ask:\n\n> A “dax” is a tool used to remove seeds from fruit.  \n> Sarah used the dax on an apple. What did Sarah use?\n\nExpected:\n\n> The dax, a seed-removing tool.\n\nOr:\n\n> This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> wugs.\n\nThis is also behavioral, but it specifically probes whether the system can handle a **novel lexical item**.\n\n---\n\n## Key distinction\n\n| Dimension | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation | Coinage probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Broad | Narrow |\n| Main method | Give inputs, inspect outputs | Give inputs containing coined/nonce words |\n| What it tests | Any capability: reasoning, syntax, factuality, planning, etc. | Novel-word learning, morphology, compositionality, abstraction |\n| Requires internal model access? | No | No |\n| Requires invented words? | Not necessarily | Yes, typically |\n| Example | “Can the model solve syllogisms?” | “Can the model infer what a ‘blicket’ is?” |\n\n---\n\n## Conceptual relationship\n\nA **coinage probe** is usually a **behavioral capability evaluation**, but with a special purpose: reducing reliance on memorized lexical knowledge.\n\nFor example, if you test:\n\n> A baker bakes bread. What does a teacher teach?\n\nThe model may answer from memorized language statistics.\n\nBut if you test:\n\n> A daxer daxes things. What does a glipper do?\n\nyou are testing whether the model can infer patterns from structure rather than simply recall familiar word associations.\n\nThat makes coinage probes useful for evaluating:\n\n- **productive morphology**\n- **nonce-word generalization**\n- **in-context lexical learning**\n- **syntactic category inference**\n- **semantic role assignment**\n- **compositional reasoning with unfamiliar terms**\n- **abstraction away from memorized vocabulary**\n\n---\n\n## Important nuance\n\nNot every behavioral probe is a coinage probe, but most coinage probes are behavioral probes.\n\nThe relationship is roughly:\n\n> capability evaluation  \n> → behavioral probe  \n> → coinage/nonce-word probe\n\nA coinage probe is therefore not an alternative to behavioral evaluation; it is a particular design strategy within behavioral evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## How it differs from ordinary capability evaluation\n\nA standard capability evaluation might ask:\n\n> Can the model translate French?  \n> Can it solve math problems?  \n> Can it answer biology questions?\n\nA coinage probe asks something more controlled:\n\n> If I remove familiar lexical items and replace them with invented ones, does the model still display the relevant ability?\n\nFor example, instead of testing arithmetic with familiar nouns:\n\n> Alice has 3 apples and gets 2 more apples. How many apples?\n\nyou might use coined terms:\n\n> Alice has 3 daxes and gets 2 more daxes. How many daxes?\n\nThis checks whether the model’s arithmetic behavior survives when familiar semantic cues are stripped away.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nA **coinage probe** is a **specific behavioral probe** using invented words to test generalization. A **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is the broader category of input-output tests of what a model can do. The distinctive value of coinage probes is that they help separate **true abstraction/generalization** from **memorized associations with familiar words**.",
