        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** overlap, but they are not identical.\n\n## Short version\n\n- A **coinage probe** uses **coined / nonce words** as stimuli to test whether a system can generalize beyond familiar vocabulary.\n- A **lexical-acquisition test** specifically tests whether a learner or model can **learn and retain a new lexical item**, usually including its meaning, usage, syntactic category, or associations.\n\nSo:\n\n> A lexical-acquisition test asks: “Did the system learn this new word?”  \n> A coinage probe asks more broadly: “How does the system handle an invented word?”\n\nA lexical-acquisition test can use coinages, but not every coinage probe is a lexical-acquisition test.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a lexical-acquisition test\n\nYou introduce a new word:\n\n> A **blicket** is a small tool used for opening jars.\n\nThen later ask:\n\n> What is a blicket?  \n> Which object is the blicket?  \n> Can a blicket be used to open a jar?  \n> Maria lost her blicket. What did she lose?\n\nThis tests whether the model or person acquired the lexical entry:\n\n> **blicket** → small jar-opening tool\n\nThe focus is on **learning a new word meaning** and possibly retaining or applying it.\n\n---\n\n## Example of a coinage probe that is not mainly lexical acquisition\n\nYou ask:\n\n> This is a wug. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> wugs.\n\nHere the point is not primarily whether the person learned a rich meaning for **wug**. The point is whether they apply the English plural rule to a novel noun.\n\nThat is a **coinage probe** of **productive morphology**, not necessarily a lexical-acquisition test.\n\nAnother example:\n\n> Someone who daxes is a ___.\n\nExpected:\n\n> daxer.\n\nAgain, the focus is word-formation generalization, not learning the meaning of **dax**.\n\n---\n\n## Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Broader | Narrower in purpose |\n| Main manipulation | Use invented / nonce words | Teach or expose a learner to a new word |\n| Main question | “Can the system handle novel lexical material?” | “Has the system learned this word?” |\n| Typical target | Morphology, syntax, compositionality, abstraction, in-context learning | Word meaning, reference, usage, retention |\n| Requires assigning a meaning? | Not always | Usually yes |\n| Requires testing retention? | Not necessarily | Often yes |\n| Example | “Two wugs” | “What is a blicket?” after exposure |\n| Relation | May include lexical learning | May use coined words as materials |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test can be implemented as a coinage probe** if the word being learned is invented.\n\nFor example:\n\n> A **toma** is a red triangular toy.  \n> Point to the toma.\n\nThis is both:\n\n1. a **coinage probe**, because **toma** is novel, and  \n2. a **lexical-acquisition test**, because the task is to learn and use the new word.\n\nBut a coinage probe can test things other than lexical acquisition, such as:\n\n- pluralization: **wug → wugs**\n- derivation: **dax → daxer**\n- syntactic category inference: “She blicked the ball” implies **blick** is a verb\n- compositionality: “red blicket” versus “small blicket”\n- analogy: “A painter paints; a glommer gloms”\n- robustness to unfamiliar vocabulary\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA lexical-acquisition test usually cares about the formation of a **new lexical entry**:\n\n> form + meaning + syntactic behavior + possible usage constraints\n\nA coinage probe may care only about whether the model can apply an existing rule to an unfamiliar form.\n\nFor instance:\n\n> There are two daxes.\n\nA model does not need to know what a **dax** is to pluralize it correctly. It only needs to infer that **dax** behaves like a count noun.\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n> **Lexical-acquisition test:** learning a word.  \n> **Coinage probe:** using a made-up word to test some capability, which may or may not involve learning the word.",
